docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — John H. Durham, the special counsel appointed by the Trump administration to scrutinize the Russia investigation, has told the Justice Department that he will ask a grand jury to indict a prominent cybersecurity lawyer on a charge of making a false statement to the F.B.I., people familiar with the matter said.

docs.abstract: Appearing with Ukraine’s foreign minister, Secretary of State Antony J. Blinken said the intentions behind Moscow’s latest military buildup were unclear.
docs.snippet: Appearing with Ukraine’s foreign minister, Secretary of State Antony J. Blinken said the intentions behind Moscow’s latest military buildup were unclear.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Secretary of State Antony J. Blinken said on Wednesday that Russia’s intentions behind its latest military buildup along Ukraine’s eastern border were unclear, but that Moscow would be making a “serious mistake” by committing new aggression against its embattled neighbor.

headline.main: Blinken Warns Russia Against Making a ‘Serious Mistake’ in Ukraine
headline.print_headline: Blinken Warns Russia Against Making a ‘Serious Mistake’ With Ukraine

docs.abstract: One of the most comprehensive studies to date of weaponry in the war in Ukraine shows a panoply of Russian-supplied arms that has helped fuel the war.

docs.lead_paragraph: KYIV, Ukraine — A study of weapons and ammunition used in the war in Ukraine shows that Russia has been systematically fanning the conflict with arms shipments, according to a new report funded by the European Union and the German government.

headline.main: Weapons Tracing Study Implicates Russia in Ukraine Conflict

docs.lead_paragraph: As the border crisis along the European Union’s eastern flank has intensified, President Aleksandr G. docs.abstract: Big oil producers decided to stick with a scheduled increase, rejecting calls for a bigger jump in production.

docs.lead_paragraph: Officials from the Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries, Russia and other oil-producing nations shook off pressure from the Biden administration and decided on Thursday to stick with their previous plan to raise oil production by a modest 400,000 barrels a day next month.
